= Why This Model Works

== Psychological Principles

=== Autonomy
People resist being told what to do but love making their own choices. The Playground model gives complete autonomy while still guiding the journey.

=== Reciprocity
The free workshop creates genuine goodwill. No sales pitch means the value is pure gift, triggering natural reciprocity.

=== Loss Aversion
At £20 per workshop, the "loss" of skipping an interesting topic hurts more than the cost. This drives attendance without pressure.

=== Social Proof
As the WhatsApp community grows, FOMO (fear of missing out) naturally attracts more members. Testimonials become powerful.

=== Commitment & Consistency
Small commitments (free workshop) lead to larger ones (trial) which lead to regular engagement (playground). Each step feels natural.

== Competitive Advantages

*vs Traditional Cooking Classes*:
- More flexible scheduling
- Lower price point
- Business-focused content
- Online + offline options
- Community aspect

*vs Online Courses*:
- Live interaction with expert
- Networking opportunities
- Immediate Q&A
- Cultural authenticity
- Practical, actionable content

*vs Consulting Services*:
- Lower barrier to entry
- Learn before committing to consulting
- Peer learning benefits
- Ongoing relationship vs one-time engagement

== Risk Mitigation

*What if people only attend free workshops?* \
That's okay. They're building brand awareness and may buy products or refer others.

*What if £20 workshops don't fill?* \
Lower prices to £15 or bundle topics. The flexibility allows rapid adjustment.

*What if customers never commit to packages?* \
They don't need to. 10 workshops at £20 = £200 organically.

*What if competition copies the model?* \
Execution, expertise, and community are hard to replicate. Bo's authenticity is the moat.

